</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distributed throughout mostly tropical regions of Asia, Australasia, and Oceania.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="gallery system">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gallery system.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This appears to have been described only in 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. insulindicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="insulindicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. insulindicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Eggers, 1923), a species not found in the study region. Based on observations in Fiji, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222937700770181" author="Roberts, H" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="251 - 272" refId="B332" refString="Roberts, H, 1977. Observations on the biology of some tropical rain forest Scolytidae (Coleoptera) from Fiji II. Subfamily Ipinae - tribe Xyleborini. Journal of Natural History 11: 251 - 272, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00222937700770181" title="Observations on the biology of some tropical rain forest Scolytidae (Coleoptera) from Fiji II. Subfamily Ipinae - tribe Xyleborini." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222937700770181" volume="11" year="1977">Roberts (1977)</bibRefCitation>
notes a short radial gallery, penetrating 2-4 cm, with several longitudinal galleries parallel to the stem axis, all in the same plane, and without enlarged brood chambers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
